      usage: "In Greek literature, 'makarios' described the blessed state of the gods — above the uncertainties and griefs of ordinary human life. Jesus appropriated this word and applied it to the poor in spirit, the mourning, the persecuted — the very people whom the world would consider cursed. He was inverting the world's value system entirely: what the world sees as cursed (meekness, mourning, persecution) is, in the economy of God's kingdom, the very condition in which blessedness is most deeply experienced.",
      connection: "When you feel overlooked, grieving, misunderstood, or persecuted for your faith — Jesus says makarios. Not because suffering is pleasant, but because God's kingdom is present and active even in the darkest circumstances, and those who are poor in spirit are precisely the ones most aware of their need for the God who fills them. Makarios is not a feeling — it is a status granted by the King.",
