    memoryVerse: "And the multitudes that went before, and that followed, cried, saying, Hosanna to the son of David: Blessed is he that cometh in the name of the Lord; Hosanna in the highest. — Matthew 21:9",
    closingPrayer: "King Jesus — You entered Jerusalem on a donkey when a war horse was available. You chose the humble path when the crowd offered You the triumphant one. Help me follow the same King in the same manner — not demanding that You be the kind of king I want, but trusting that You are the kind of king I need. When I cry Hosanna — save me — remind me that You already know what I need to be saved from, even when I don't. Amen.",

    leaderNote: "Week 35 is the hinge between the Galilean ministry and the Passion week. The theological key is the crowd's expectation versus Jesus' intention — this is not merely a Palm Sunday lesson but a lesson about what we project onto Jesus versus what He actually offers. The 'Hosanna/Crucify' reversal is the most powerful illustration of following Jesus for wrong reasons, and teens need to hear it named. The de Gaulle illustration is historically solid and accessible — it illustrates the 'donkey path' without being preachy. The journal prompt is theologically mature: inviting teens to reflect on times God saved them from something other than what they asked. Transition lesson: connect to next week by noting that the donkey path leads to a table, and the table leads to a cross.",
